Make lentil soup with me…

Sharing my moms famous (daal) lentil soup recipe for this cold weather to warm you up. 💕

Daal (Lentil soup) Recipe:
Serves 5-6

Ingredients:
I cup masoor daal (red lentils)
I cup moong daal (orange lentils)
1 TBSP @shanfoodsglobal ginger and garlic paste
Pink salt to taste
1 large onion sliced 
1 TSP haldi (turmeric) powder
1 TSP red chili powder
7-8 whole dried red chillies
3 small tomatoes puréed 
1 bay leaf
6-7 cups water

For the tarka (topping for the daal):
1 TSP cumin seeds
1/2 onion sliced 
3-5 garlic cloves chopped
1 TBSP butter 
1/3 cup cooking oil 

Method:
Combine the two daals, water, chili powder, turmeric, onions salt and ginger garlic paste. Cover and cook until boiling for about 20 mins. Add the tomato purée and whole dried red chillies. Cover and cook for an hour on medium to low heat while stirring occasionally. 

In another sauce pan, add the oil, butter, cumin seeds, onions, chopped garlic and salt. Stir for about 6-8 mins slightly browning the onions. Then add to the daal (lentil) pot while hot and cover for 5 mins. Garnish with chopped coriander and serve with boiled rice or naan.

This is such an easy yet healthy recipe that is also perfect for those that are on a vegan diet!

Peri Peri Chicken Sliders

Perfect for Ramadan Iftars, Eid or any occasion, these scrumptious crowd pleasing, gooey, cheesy and spicy sliders will keep you reaching for more! @walmart #walmarthome #walmartpartner 

Recipe:

Homemade peri peri seasoning:
1 TBSP paprika
1 TBSP crushed red chili flakes 
1 TBSP chilli powder
1/2 TBSP garlic powder 
1/2 TBSP onion powder 
1 TBSP oregano
1 TBSP salt
1 TBSP pepper (table grind)

Ingredients:
2 LBS boneless chicken breast
5 TSP fresh minced garlic
2 chopped green chillies or jalapeños 
6 sprigs fresh cilantro 
4-5 TBSP Nandos peri peri sauce 
3 TBSP oil
1/2 onion diced 
Havarti cheese slices or any cheese of your choice
(I used Havarti cheese slices)
Mozzarella cheese as desired 

For the garlic butter:
3 TBSP butter
2 tsp minced garlic
2 TBSP chopped fresh cilantro 

Method:
In a bowl combine the boneless cubes of chicken, homemade peri peri seasoning and 3 tsp of fresh minced garlic. Mix well and marinate for 30 mins. In a sauté pan, add a tsp of oil and sauté the diced onion until golden. Now add the marinated chicken and sauté for about 20 mins or until golden brown. Then add the peri peri sauce followed by the green chillies and continue sautéing for another 5 mins. Remove from heat. 

Slice open the center of the sliders and remove the top while keeping it intact. Assemble the sliders with the cheese slices, red onions, cooked chicken and top with lots of shredded mozzarella cheese. Bake at 400 degrees for about 6 mins or until cheese is melted. Korma is Pakistani comfort food to me. If you haven’t tried it yet, you will fall in love when you do! It’s super easy to make and I was fortunate enough to learn this recipe from my mom 🥹 I hope you can try this for yourself because making Korma the right way is a privilege 💛

Chicken Korma Recipe 📝
Serves 5-6

Ingredients:
 
Chicken (Bone in cut up in small pieces 2-3LBS)
1 cup vegetable oil or ghee
1 onion sliced 
2-3 TBSP yoghurt 
1 TSP kewra water
1 TSP ginger paste 
1 TSP garlic paste 
1 1/2 - 2 cups water (Use less if you want a thicker gravy)

Whole seasonings:
2 star anise 
1 cinnamon stick
2 bay leaves 
4 cloves 
4 black cardamom 
5 green cardamom 
1/2 TSP whole back peppercorn 

Powder Seasonings:

1 TSP salt
1 1/2 TSP Kashmiri red chili powder 
1 TSP coriander powder 
1 1/2 TSP turmeric powder 

Method:
In a large pot heat the oil and add the sliced onion. When lightly golden brown, remove the onions on parchment paper and set aside. Now in the same pot add all the whole seasoning and stir until fragrant. Add the chicken followed by the ginger and garlic paste and stir well until mixed and the chicken gets golden brown. Now add all the powder seasonings and continue to stir until combined. 

In a blender, blender together the yoghurt and onions that we had set aside. Then add the yoghurt mixture to the pot and combine. Add the water followed by the kewra water and let it cook for about 6-8 mins wit the lid on. 

Serve with naan or sheermal 💛

Ingredients:

2-3 LBS goat meat 
Salt to taste (I used 2 TBSP)
2 TBSP table grind black pepper 
2 TSP ginger and garlic paste
4-5 TBSP vegetable oil
4-5 TBSP plain yoghurt 
5-6 chopped Roma tomatoes 
7-8 Serrano peppers or green chillies chopped 
1 bunch cilantro chopped for garnish

Method:

Wash the meat and add to a pot filled with water, 2 tsps salt and a ladle of oil. Cover and boil for about 2 hours or until meat is tender. 

Prepare and chop all the vegetables and set aside. Once the meat is tender, add the ginger garlic paste and chopped tomatoes to the pot. Cover and cook until the tomatoes are soft. Remove the tomato peels and continue to cook while stirring for another 30 mins or until the tomatoes have completely dissolved. Now add the chopped green chillies and yoghurt and continue to stir until the oil has separated from the curry. 

Add the chopped cilantro for garnish and serve with naans or rice. Enjoy!

How do I choose the correct artificial flower arrangement for my home? Keep reading to find out

When choosing faux florals for your home, consider the following tips:

1. Quality: Look for high-quality faux florals that closely resemble real flowers and plants. Pay attention to details like texture, color variations, and realistic-looking leaves and petals. Avoid cheap-looking or overly plastic-looking options.

2. Realism: Opt for faux florals that mimic the appearance of real flowers and plants. Look for natural-looking shapes, sizes, and proportions. Consider the type of flowers or plants you want to replicate and choose faux versions that capture their essence.

3. Maintenance: Opt for low-maintenance faux florals that require minimal upkeep. Choose materials that are easy to clean and dust, and avoid options that easily fade or deteriorate over time. This will ensure that your faux florals continue to look fresh and vibrant for longer.

4. Versatility: Select faux florals that can be easily incorporated into different styles and spaces. Consider the color scheme and overall aesthetic of your home and choose florals that complement the existing decor. Additionally, opt for versatile arrangements that can be easily rearranged or repurposed in different rooms or seasons.

By considering these factors, you can choose faux florals that add beauty and a touch of nature to your home without the need for constant maintenance or worry about wilting.

Papa is constantly experimenting in the kitchen since my mom passed away and came up with this scrumptious restaurant style chicken ginger recipe which is pretty famous in Pakistan. Sharing it below so make sure you save this!! Simply put, it’s better than the restaurants! 🙌🏼

Here’s the recipe:

Ingredients:
4LBS boneless chicken thighs cubed 
1 TBSP ginger paste 
1 ginger root finely sliced 
1 bulb of garlic cloves 
1 large onion 
7-8 tomatoes sliced in half
1 cup water 
1/2 cup ghee or 1 stick of butter 
8 TBSP plain yoghurt 
3 TBSP heavy cream 
3-4 slices green chillies
3 TBSP chopped cilantro for garnish

Spice seasonings:
1 TBSP cumin seeds
1 TBSP chili flakes 
1 TBSP red chili powder
1 TBSP salt
1 TBSP black pepper 
1 TBSP garam masala powder 
1 TSP dried fenugreek (kasuri methi)

Method:
In a small pot add the water, sliced onions, garlic cloves and tomatoes. Cover the lid and cook until all the vegetables have softened about 20-30 minutes. After everything has softened, sieve, add to a blender and set aside the blended mixture.

In a separate pot add the butter, ginger paste and cubed chicken and stir. Add the cumin seeds, red chili powder, chili flakes and salt along with the blended mixture of vegetables and stir on high heat reducing the water content. After the water from the pot has been reduced, add the yoghurt, black pepper and garam masala followed by the finely sliced ginger, green chillies and the fenugreek powder. Finally add the cream and garnish with the chopped cilantro. 

Serve immediately with warm naan or rice!
